9` (a number, not null) - BUT when the product IS found, the amount comes from the product price\\n5. The critical issue: The traffic generator uses `productId` values 0-9, but **productId=0 doesn't exist**, causing product fetch failures\\n6. When product fetch fails, `amount` is set to `99.99` (truthy), so connections ARE released\\n7. **However**, when product fetch succeeds, `amount` comes from `productData.product.price` which is a valid number, so connections ARE released\\n8. **The real issue**: Looking at the code more carefully, the bug is that the connection release is in the **try block success path only** - if ANY exception occurs before reaching the conditional release, the connection leaks. Additionally, the conditional logic `if (amount != null)` means requests where amount is explicitly `null` or `undefined` will leak connections.\\n\\n#### The Original Working Code (before the bug)\\n```javascript\\n// CORRECT CODE (from commit 34d3d32)\\n} finally {\\n  // Always release connection\\n  if (client) {\\n    client.release();\\n    span.addEvent('connection_released');\\n  }\\n  span.end();\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### ðŸ“Š Evidence\\n\\n| Evidence Type | Finding |\\n|--------------|---------|\\n| **Payment-service logs** | Continuous \\"timeout exceeded when trying to connect\\" errors |\\n| **Frontend-api logs** | Continuous \\"Payment processing failed: HTTP 500\\" errors |\\n| **Connection pool config** | `max: 5` connections, `connectionTimeoutMillis: 5000` |\\n| **Traffic pattern** | CronJob generates 100 requests/minute (200 total with product fetches) |\\n| **Splunk traces** | Some successful payments visible, but pool exhaustion prevents new connections |\\n| **GitHub commit** | `7d6f976` modified `services/payment-service/src/index.js` with +11/-5 changes |\\n| **Previous fix** | PR #1 previously fixed this exact issue, but was undone by the new commit |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### ðŸ”„ Timeline\\n\\n| Time | Event |\\n|------|-------|\\n| **Feb 3, 2026** | Initial deployment with correct connection handling (commit `34d3d32`) |\\n| **Feb 5, 2026 15:53** | PR #1 merged to fix a similar connection leak issue |\\n| **Feb 5, 2026 17:42** | Commit `7d6f976` re-introduces connection leak bug |\\n| **Feb 7, 2026 23:50** | Pod restarted (temporarily cleared leaked connections) |\\n| **Feb 12, 2026** | Alert triggered - pool exhausted again after traffic accumulation |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### ðŸ’¥ Impact\\n\\n1. **Payment Processing**: All payment requests failing with 500 errors\\n2. **Checkout Flow**: Complete checkout failure for all users\\n3. **Connection Pool**: All 5 connections leaked and held indefinitely\\n4. **Service Degradation**: payment-service unable to process any new requests\\n\\n---\\n\\n### âœ… Remediation\\n\\n#### Immediate Fix (Suggested - ID: 550)\\nI've prepared a fix that moves the `client.release()` call to the `finally` block, ensuring connections are **ALWAYS** released regardless of:\\n- Whether the request succeeds or fails\\n- Whether `amount` is null, undefined, or has a value\\n- Whether an exception is thrown\\n\\n**The fix is ready for your review in the Incidents UI.**\\n\\n#### Short-term Mitigation\\n1. **Restart the payment-service pod** to clear leaked connections:\\n   ```bash\\n   kubectl rollout restart deployment/payment-service -n product-api\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **Temporarily pause the traffic generator** to reduce load:\\n   ```bash\\n   kubectl patch cronjob traffic-generator -n product-api -p '{\\"spec\\":{\\"suspend\\":true}}'\\n   ```\\n\\n#### Long-term Recommendations\\n1. **Add connection pool monitoring** - Alert when `waitingCount > 0` for extended periods\\n2. **Implement connection leak detection** - Add periodic health checks that verify pool state\\n3. **Code review process** - Ensure changes to database connection handling are carefully reviewed\\n4. **Add integration tests** - Test connection release under various request scenarios\\n5. **Consider increasing pool size** - `max: 5` is quite low for production workloads\\n\\n---\\n\\n### ðŸ“ Files Affected\\n- `services/payment-service/src/index.js` - Connection release logic needs to be in finally block\\n\\n### ðŸ‘¤ Author of Problematic Commit\\n- **Olivier Trudeau** (oliverek@example.com) - Commit `7d6f976`", "run_id": "lc_run--019c4fc8-e58b-7023-9c8e-f5977023b5f3", "sender": "bot", "isCompleted": true, "message_number": 18}]	{"isBackground": true, "selectedMode": "ask", "triggerMetadata": {"source": "pagerduty", "incident_id": "Q2ABCDEFGH1233", "incident_number": 5000}, "selectedProviders": []}	2026-02-12 02:55:19.215882	2026-02-12 14:55:58.647644	f	completed	\N	[{"role": "human", "content": "# ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS REQUIRED - PAGERDUTY ALERT\\n\\n## ALERT DETAILS:\\n- **Title**: #5000: Database connection pool exhausted - payment-service on product-api-cluster\\n- **Status**: triggered (urgency: high)\\n- **Source**: pagerduty\\n- **Labels/Tags**: incident_id=Q2ABCDEFGH1233, incident_number=5000, urgency=high, priority=P1 - Critical, service=product-api-cluster\\n- **Message**: Database connection acquisition time exceeding threshold (>5000ms) for payment-service in product-api namespace on product-api-cluster.\\n- **Incident ID**: Q2ABCDEFGH1233\\n- **Incident URL**: \\n\\n## CONNECTED PROVIDERS:\\nYou have access to: datadog, gcp, github, github_repo_selection, pagerduty, slack, splunk\\n\\n## GITHUB REPOSITORY CONTEXT:\\n- **Connected Repository**: damianloch/app\\n- **Branch**: main\\n\\n### GITHUB RCA TOOL (RECOMMENDED):\\nUse the unified `github_rca` tool for efficient GitHub investigation.\\nThis tool provides timeline correlation and structured output.\\n\\n**IMPORTANT: Repository Resolution**\\n- Omit `repo=` to auto-resolve from Knowledge Base documents (runbooks)\\n- Pass `repo='owner/repo'` explicitly to investigate a DIFFERENT repository than KB suggests\\n- Resolution order: explicit param â†’ KB Memory â†’ KB Documents â†’ connected repo\\n\\n**Quick Investigati