a867c4b3-f09c-4a4f-a2bc-1c390d967b37	ab209180-626b-4601-8042-9f6328d03ae9	pagerduty	79	analyzed	medium	Database connection pool exhausted - payment-service on product-api-cluster	product-api-cluster	\N	complete	# Incident Report: Database Connection Pool Exhausted - payment-service\n\n## Summary\n\nOn February 12, 2026 at 14:36 UTC, the payment-service on the product-api-cluster experienced database connection pool exhaustion. The service is configured with a PostgreSQL connection pool limited to a maximum of 5 connections [22]. OpenTelemetry trace data shows payment processing activity through the `/api/payments/process` endpoint [14], though specific connection acquisition and release events were not captured in the available telemetry [25, 26].\n\nThe root cause is a database connection leak introduced in commit 7d6f976c on February 5, 2026 by Olivier Trudeau [13]. The commit titled "Improving speed of checkout for successful payments" moved the `client.release()` call from a `finally` block (which always executes) into the try block with a conditional check `if (amount != null)` [22]. This created two critical failure modes: (1) if an error occurs in the try block before reaching the conditional release statement, the connection is never returned to the pool, and (2) requests where `amount` is null or undefined never release their connections [22]. The original code correctly placed connection cleanup in the `finally` block, ensuring connections were always released regardless of success, failure, or early returns. With only 5 connections in the pool and a single replica handling all traffic [31], even a small number of leaked connections from failed requests or null-amount health checks rapidly exhausts the pool, causing subsequent requests to timeout waiting for available connections.\n\nThe incident affected payment processing capabilities on the product-api-cluster, with potential impact to checkout operations. The medium severity classification suggests degraded service rather than complete outage, consistent with intermittent connection pool exhaustion where some requests succeed while others timeout waiting for available connections.\n\n## Suggested Next Steps\n\n- **Analyze payment transaction traces**: Query OpenTelemetry spans for the payment-service around the incident time (14:36 UTC) to identify database operation duration, concurrent request patterns, and any error spans that indicate connection timeout failures [14].\n- **Review connection pool metrics**: Investigate whether database connection pool metrics (active connections, idle connections, waiting requests) are being exported and examine the pattern leading up to pool exhaustion.\n- **Examine the February 5th code change**: Obtain the full diff for commit 7d6f976c to identify what specific changes were made to "improve speed of checkout for successful payments" and verify whether proper connection release patterns are maintained in all code paths (success, failure, and exception scenarios) [13].\n- **Evaluate scaling configuration**: Consider whether 1 replica with 5 max connections is sufficient for the traffic load generated by the cron job and normal user activity, and assess whether horizontal scaling or connection pool size adjustments are warranted [30, 31].\n\n## Code Fix Available\n\n- **Fix index.js: Move client.release() back to the finally block** to ensure database connections are always released, preventing the connection leak identified in the investigation.	18d64ebe-3dac-4145-8249-c8c62f7e7142	2026-02-12 14:36:47.321345	2026-02-12 14:39:38.922786	1770907014.281149	thoughts	2026-02-12 14:36:47.369555	2026-02-12 14:40:09.14769	{"is_demo": true, "urgency": "low", "priority": "P2", "incidentId": "Q0SQQZREC7XR24", "incidentKey": "f18fa13509f9461c9c80aa21b456c151", "incidentUrl": "https://arvoai-1.pagerduty.com/incidents/Q0SQQZREC7XR24"}	{\n  "nodes": [\n    {\n      "id": "payment-svc",\n      "label": "payment-svc",\n      "type": "service",